"The New York Times", "subsection_name": "Africa", "lead_paragraph": "The practice of depleting the forest for precious fuel during hard times has been taking a toll at taps in the capital city, Lilongwe.", "pub_date": "2016-08-20T16:34:06+0000", "news_desk": "Foreign", "headline": {"print_headline": "Drought and Felled Trees Take a Toll at Malawi\u2019s Taps", "main": "Poverty, Drought and Felled Trees Imperil Malawi Water Supply"}, "print_page": "5", "snippet": "The practice of depleting the forest for precious fuel during hard times has been taking a toll at taps in the capital city, Lilongwe....", "_id": "57b8868495d0e021d7981baf", "slideshow_credits": null, "abstract": "Rampant deforestation of Dzalanyama Forest Reserve in Malawi for illegal production of charcoal has lead to unprecedented level of environmental degradation in country; forest is catchment basin for Lilongwe River and destruction of trees has significantly cut forest's ability to retain and release water in rainy season; charcoal production, along with regional drought, is contributing to drastic shortage of water in capital city of Lilongwe."}